      b.raw("<article>\n    <header class=\"article-head\">\n        <h1>About this blog</h1>\n        <p class=\"post-excerpt\">Why a blog about the Internet Computer is itself running on the Internet Computer.</p>\n    </header>\n    <div class=\"article-body\">\n        <p><strong>The Canister Log</strong> is a small publication about building full-stack applications directly on the Internet Computer. Every post here is written, stored, and served from a single Motoko canister — there is no separate web server, no CDN, and no frontend JavaScript bundle.</p>\n\n        <h2>How this page reaches you</h2>\n        <p>This page is marked <code>@cacheable</code>, so the canister serves it as a <em>certified query</em>: the HTML you are reading arrives with a cryptographic proof that it really came from this canister, in milliseconds, with no update call.</p>\n\n        <h2>Built for search engines, by default</h2>\n        <p>Because MotoView renders real HTML on the server, every post ships with a correct <code>&lt;title&gt;</code>, meta description, and canonical link on the first byte. Crawlers and link previews see a complete document — no hydration, no waiting for a script to run.</p>\n\n        <h2>The stack</h2>\n        <ul>\n            <li><strong>One actor.</strong> Pages, routing, and content compile into a single Motoko canister.</li>\n            <li><strong>Certified delivery.</strong> Public pages are served as fast, verifiable queries.</li>\n            <li><strong>No frontend JavaScript.</strong> The browser only swaps DOM the canister already rendered.</li>\n        </ul>\n\n        <p>Want to see it in motion? Head back to the <a href=\"/\">latest posts</a>.</p>\n    </div>\n    <a class=\"back-link\" href=\"/\">← Back to all posts</a>\n</article>\n");
